stories: Bias triangles are a type of feature that can be found in stability diagrams of quantum dot (QD) devices, and understanding their occurrence and properties is important for spin physics research. However, there have been challenges associated with the quality and availability of data as well as the complexity of the physical phenomena involved that have made it difficult to develop an automatic analysis framework for bias triangles. Often, this has relied on human labelling and verification to some degree. In this work, we introduce a feature extraction framework for bias triangles based on unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods that allows for the direct identification and quantification of their physical properties. By doing so, the need for human input or large training datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is avoided, while also enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and feature labelling. Specifically, we show that Pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection can be performed effectively, efficiently, and without any training data using this approach.
